	   <tr><td colspan=2>And I'm having trouble believing this is coming from a lvl 59 monk, personally.<br><br>As you said, if you are making a monk (or any character) with the intention of getting to the high levels, then Stamina investment can surely pay off.&nbsp;&nbsp;Fist off, most high level monks use SoS in their off hand even when they have CFs..  Why?  Cause SoS does MORE dmg then their off hand fist would, not to mention the effect on it helps a lot.  That alone is 3.2 wt, which doesn't seem like much, but monk with maxed haste around 55-60 DW's a huge amount.  Before they get their CFs, weapon of choice in prime hand is generally Jaded Mace, another 2.1 wt.  Combined that's a lot of wt for a monk to be swinging with maxed haste.  Even with Jade Mace and KD (1.0 wt) in off hand, high level monk hasted tends to run outta stamina before long with long fights or constant pulling.  I should know, my 55 druid is always pumping out Extinguish Fatigues to satiate the monk I often grouped with.  And those were the weapons he wielded.  I might also add, jade mace is best in prime hand till you get Celestial Fists, KD is better ratio in off hand until 56 (human monk, 58th for iksar I believe).<br><br>Now, with extinguish fatigue spell, it's not such a huge problem usually.  But at the highest levels, expecially 55-60, one of the major things people do is participate in raids.  And the big boss mobs really don't care about AC, on the final encounter in a raid (or any boss type mob) HP and resists are what count.  That mob will smack ya for 2 k in one round, and if a monk happens to draw their attention...which isn't there goal, the more hp they have, better chance of survival. <br><br>On top of just having more base HP, your mend will be more effective.  Not to mention allowing you to better survive bad pulls with casters and/or failed FDs.<br><br>I wish I had known this when I created my 3rd monk (tried Iksar before going back to human).  I thought I would be fixing him by sinking points into str.  I won't argue that it helps increase damage output.  But at same time, more and more tests and personal experiences are showing the over all gain in dmg from str is relatively minor, which we already do plenty.  We know at lvl 50, 1 sta = 4 hp.  That doesn't mean much, but add up starting 20 points, that's 80 hp and another 20 from mend.  That IS a noticeable improvement, adding in other stamina gear only further helps it.<br><br>More and more I'm hearing from my high level monk friends how they are going for Stamina/hp and Resists (never shocked about that) gear over just about any other type.  Also, my monk who is 47th atm misses the stamina buff from my shaman partner more than any other stat buff.<br><br>In closing, anyone starting a monk and planning on the long run and getting over lvl 50 would be well served to invest least part if not all points into stamina, can NEVER have too many HPs as a monk.  You WILL end up tanking sometimes, warrior in group or not, you WILL agro boss mobs onto you if only for a round it may be your last, you WILL have crazy/bad pulls and every bit of HP will help.  But of course, I'm not gonna make anyone put points into stamina, that's entirely up to each person and what they want, but I will strongly suggest it.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
